  <section class="col col-space-m col-720">
    <h3>Funding for training to teach chemistry</h3>

    <p>To train to be a chemistry teacher, you'll need to do a teacher training course.</p>

<p>Bursaries of £28,000 and scholarships of £30,000 are available for <a href="https://getintoteaching.education.gov.uk/funding-and-support/scholarships-and-bursaries?funding_widget%5Bsubject%5D=chemistry&button=#funding-widget">eligible trainee chemistry teachers</a>.</p><p>

You can receive this alongside a tuition fee and maintenance loan.</p>

<p>You may also be able to get extra funding support if you are:</p>
<ul><li>
a parent or carer</li>
<li>disabled</li>
</ul>
<p>Non-UK citizens without indefinite leave to remain in the UK are unlikely to be eligible for funding.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="col col-space-m col-720">
    <h3>Check your qualifications</h3>
    <p>You'll need a bachelors degree before training to teach but it does not have to be in chemistry. Alongside chemistry, The most popular degrees people have before doing a teacher training course in chemistry are:</p>
<ul>
  <li>biomedical sciences</li>
<li>forensic science</li>
<li>pharmacology  </li>
</ul>

<p>To train to teach in primary and secondary schools in England, you’ll need:</p>
<ul>
<li>GCSEs at grade 4 (C) or above in English and maths (and science if you want to teach primary)</li>
<li>a bachelor’s degree in any subject</li>
</ul>

<p>Your training provider may need you to brush up on your computing knowledge before you become a computing teacher. You can do a <a href="https://getintoteaching.education.gov.uk/how-to-apply-for-teacher-training/subject-knowledge-enhancement">subject knowledge enhancement (SKE) course</a> before you start your teacher training to top up your subject knowledge.</p>


    <p>
      <a href="/is-teaching-right-for-me/qualifications-you-need-to-teach">Find out about the qualifications needed to teach</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="col col-space-m col-720">
    <h3>Paid internship</h3>

    <p>
     If you’re currently doing an undergraduate or master's degree and are interested in teaching computing, you could apply for a <a href="https://getintoteaching.education.gov.uk/is-teaching-right-for-me/teaching-internship-providers">paid teaching internship</a>.</p>

<p>The 3 week programme could help you to understand what it’s really like in the classroom and get a feel for school life.</p>
<p>You can also find out what it's like to be in a classroom through <a href="https://getintoteaching.education.gov.uk/is-teaching-right-for-me/get-school-experience">unpaid school experience</a>. </p>
